The paper deals with the construction of graph spanners, which is a fundamental topic in distributed computing and graph theory. The paper specifically focuses on the construction of near-additive spanners in the CONGEST model, which is a well-studied model in distributed computing. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing). The paper also involves graph algorithms and data structures, which are typical topics in cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The paper also involves network algorithms and protocols, which are typical topics in cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture). The paper also involves the analysis of algorithms and complexity theory, which are typical topics in cs.AL (Computational Complexity). Finally, the paper involves computational geometry, which is a typical topic in cs.CG (Computational Geometry).
